{{italic title}} In [[feudal law]], '''Nulle terre sans seigneur''' is the principle that one provides services to the [[sovereignty|sovereign]] (usually serving in his [[army]]) for the right to receive land from the sovereign. Originally a maxim of feudal law<ref>{{cite book |title=Black's Law Dictionary |publisher=West Publishing Co. |place=St. Paul, Minnesota |date=1891-2018}}</ref>, it applies in modern form to paying [[Land tax|rates or land tax]] for land of former [[Feudal system|feudal]] or feudal-like origin such as land with modern [[fee simple]] title, as opposed to land with [[Allodial title|allodial]] or [[Udal title|udal]] title.{{cn|date=May 2018}}
In the original [[French language|French]] the expression means "No land without a lord" though the legal sense might be more akin to "no property without a liege" since it was at the basis of the link between the infeodated or [[nobility|feal]] and his [[Allegiance|liege]], in the feudal system.
